    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1956-02-08T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1956-02-08T00:00:00-05:00" n="481"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d481">
                <head>481. Telegram 1467 from Geneva<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d481fn1"
                        >Source: Department of State, Central Files, 611.93/2–856. Confidential;
                        Priority; Limit Distribution.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Geneva</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1956-02-08"
                            >February 8, 1956, 11 a.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <pb facs="d481-1" n="1" type="facsimile" xml:id="d481-1"/>
                <p>1467. From <persName corresp="#p_JUA_1">Johnson</persName>.</p>
                <p>Re last sentence paragraph 3 Department telegram 1591.</p>
                <p>My recollection is that surrender by Japanese Forces on Taiwan to Chinese was
                    accomplished under general order No. 1 issued by MacArthur as SCAP rather than
                    as U.S. Commander. Would appreciate <pb facs="0776" n="729" type="typeset"
                        xml:id="pg_729"/> confirmation that our position is that this constituted
                    “capture” but that action was carried out by “forces under U.S. orders”.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_GFC_1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Gowen</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
